     FractionBox["1", "10"], ",", 
     RowBox[{"{", "\<\"-Z\"\>", "}"}]}], "}"}]}], "}"}]], "Output",
 CellLabel->
  "Out[102]= ",ExpressionUUID->"48ae5ca7-5ec8-47eb-b52b-c9326e48fcac"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The two branches are stabilized by ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"+", 
   StyleBox["Z", "TI"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "01b0d2ee-59e3-44c0-beac-a81f6d5fd63a"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"-", 
   StyleBox["Z", "TI"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "30b9a3ad-e6db-472e-a84d-1f19c89d09f9"],
 ", the ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  TemplateBox[{"0"},
   "Ket"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "75121e92-7cdc-4a7b-add9-a5767f5d463a"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  TemplateBox[{"1"},
   "Ket"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "c2b45c18-a432-4b37-b58c-f8eac42aa1b6"],
 " of a classical bit flip, with weights ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"9", "/", "10"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "95a8de58-0803-4f4a-b115-ca84f32b09f4"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"1", "/", "10"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "4482884c-0d4b-43a1-831f-7ea94226b8d1"],
 "."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"d554a002-a64b-4989-b60a-44381502831a"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "These heads, together with ",
 Cell[BoxData["PauliStabilizer"], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "0041e1dd-36aa-4356-b6c6-ed0709ced3a1"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData["StabilizerFrame"], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "ae205e37-dd65-4022-af15-917e15684343"],
 ", let one stay in the tableau picture for states, codes, graph-state \
surgery, magic accounting, and noise, inside the same object model as the \
rest of the framework."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"e6b61238-5fbc-428f-bb7b-b79dff1d344c"]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["An honest comparison with other packages", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"6388e340-bea4-4571-b4cc-c256c31cf370"],

Cell["\<\
The stabilizer simulators built for raw throughput are Stim, a C++ engine, \
and QuantumClifford.jl, a Julia package; both are excellent and both are \
narrower in scope than a general quantum framework. The fair question is \
two-sided: how close is the framework on the task they specialize in, and \
what does it offer that they do not.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"1bc2a17e-c225-4427-8593-9f4a2a3b6476"],

Cell["\<\
On gate-folding throughput the gap is now a small constant factor. The \
figures here are the measured wall-clock for an identical Clifford stream on \
an Apple M2 Pro, measured June 2026 from the framework's own bottleneck \
audit, with Stim for reference; treat them as a dated snapshot, not a \
guarantee:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"7d26b3c3-3c94-41c9-a7ce-ec74026db0cb"],

Cell[BoxData[GridBox[{
   {Cell["qubits (gates)", "TableText",
     FontWeight->Bold,ExpressionUUID->"d349c3a7-1202-465f-aed9-fc3e61e483b9"],
     Cell["QuantumFramework", "TableText",
     FontWeight->Bold,ExpressionUUID->"3a1053be-a1c4-472a-a548-ea59b89c4151"],
     Cell["Stim", "TableText",
     FontWeight->Bold,ExpressionUUID->"e8ed065c-355b-44be-8d45-ab25d955dffe"],
     Cell["ratio", "TableText",
     FontWeight->Bold,ExpressionUUID->"cdbfe9e4-022f-4164-a665-bc49a7a34f54"]},
   {Cell["100 (2k)", "TableText",ExpressionUUID->
     "69a8083a-a7ab-4672-b419-9c7fe7ea6ee6"], Cell[
    "2.6 ms", "TableText",ExpressionUUID->
     "56f01a89-c935-4cc8-b3ad-57a868ac16f2"], Cell[
    "1.03 ms", "TableText",ExpressionUUID->
     "452c95e9-c101-4ec0-9d29-8c7cb05a5d02"], Cell[
    "2.5x", "TableText",ExpressionUUID->
     "47b04e8a-647a-47b5-afcd-322b8a43935e"]},
   {Cell["500 (10k)", "TableText",ExpressionUUID->
     "ad92d023-4462-4254-9e48-0a3f5fcdafa0"], Cell[
    "26.2 ms", "TableText",ExpressionUUID->
     "4d602345-718f-4ca0-8f4f-fe415a0860aa"], Cell[
    "5.14 ms", "TableText",ExpressionUUID->
     "d33895b1-61dc-4dfd-ac5e-57c1bbc89d76"], Cell[
    "5.1x", "TableText",ExpressionUUID->
     "efa8f0d5-5525-47ff-87f6-a3e0e93fa6a0"]},
   {Cell["1000 (20k)", "TableText",ExpressionUUID->
     "57ccb37c-2e9d-4a28-ae69-7866a966570f"], Cell[
    "58.0 ms", "TableText",ExpressionUUID->
     "49173720-72d0-4bc7-a721-5f1ffc91141f"], Cell[
    "10.9 ms", "TableText",ExpressionUUID->
     "0486093e-b0c4-4a22-a16a-ed4511b59d15"], Cell[
    "5.3x", "TableText",ExpressionUUID->
     "9815ada0-5c6d-4621-b9f8-5cb4bb6cd71e"]}
  },
  GridBoxAlignment->{"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Baseline}}},
  GridBoxDividers->{"Columns" -> {{None}}, "Rows" -> {{True}}},
  GridBoxSpacings->{"Columns" -> {{1.5}}, "Rows" -> {{0.7}}}]], "Text",Express\
ionUUID->"fe955d33-cd51-44e8-aa26-79dd46d5b7cd"],

Cell["\<\
At a thousand qubits the framework also runs ahead of QuantumClifford.jl on \
the same stream (58.0 ms against 108.4 ms). The remaining gap to Stim is SIMD \
lane width, Stim packs 256-bit vector lanes against the framework's 62-bit \
machine words, plus a small per-gate circuit-encoding pass; it is a constant \
factor, not an algorithmic deficit. Getting there took compiling the gate \
fold to a single C kernel: the gate-by-gate interpreted path is 15 to 30 \
times slower, around 74, 402, and 955 ms at 100, 500, and 1000 qubits.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"3fa9d181-189a-4067-b3e8-9bc3b9c051e9"],

Cell["What the framework offers that the dedicated engines do not:", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"abcbbd79-cf96-4a5e-81db-4880c72e3da0"],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["Symbolic signs", "TI"],
 ". Outcomes can be carried as formal symbols through a circuit (the SymPhase \
method), so a single traversal serves arbitrarily many samples and the \
correlations between outcomes come out as explicit polynomials; in the \
dedicated engines the same device propagates Pauli faults to syndromes, which \
is the sampling bottleneck the technique was built to break."
}], "Item",ExpressionUUID->"a156c2aa-22bd-4054-afb6-4eeb7cae9fce"],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["Exact arithmetic", "TI"],
 ". Coefficients, signs, and the random-Clifford sampler use exact rationals, \
so seeded output is bit-reproducible and there is no floating-point drift."
}], "Item",ExpressionUUID->"9035a384-14d8-4cd8-b3c6-dc7290ad1321"],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["One object model", "TI"],
 ". A ",
 Cell[BoxData["PauliStabilizer"], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "ea9c587a-762e-4a08-adee-a1527db4a682"],
 " converts to a ",
 Cell[BoxData["QuantumState"], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "8a302f8c-82d1-4c1c-ac40-1d833d3b1e6f"],
 ", a ",
 Cell[BoxData["QuantumOperator"], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "88cec675-26d0-4158-887b-7e2a82ec7713"],
 ", a ",
 Cell[BoxData["QuantumCircuitOperator"], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "af45aaef-26f2-4286-a7f0-6db694c15f8c"],
 ", or a ",
 Cell[BoxData["QuantumChannel"], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "f28e7f18-eb7d-47f0-9644-f1653068f701"],
 ", so a stabilizer subroutine drops into a larger simulation that also uses \
dense states, density matrices, Lindblad evolution, or phase-space methods, \
without leaving the language."
}], "Item",ExpressionUUID->"9506c366-8514-4c3f-87b3-d060e94128ae"],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["Breadth of heads", "TI"],
 ". Graph states with local complementation, stabilizer frames for magic \
accounting, and Clifford channels for open-system Clifford dynamics are \
first-class objects, not features one bolts on."
}], "Item",ExpressionUUID->"097bf162-f3ae-44c7-84ac-ac05c1a9d182"],

Cell["Where the framework genuinely trails, stated plainly:", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"1f083f12-fe9e-4360-9244-1cf9023a8488"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "It is a constant factor (roughly ",
 Cell[BoxData["2.5"], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "758e4ab8-d902-48da-8fa6-53451ce8660c"],
 " to ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"5.3", "\[Times]"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "a2ce6d4a-d971-4640-827e-3b5691cbf9e0"],
 ") behind Stim on pure gate throughput, because Stim packs wider SIMD \
lanes."
}], "Item",ExpressionUUID->"10da97d0-6558-4c8b-835c-f4a4dfcae0e5"],

Cell["\<\
It has no constant-cost bulk Pauli-frame sampler, the trick that makes Stim's \
shot-by-shot sampling so cheap.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"a5fa5819-8a73-42d7-b4a8-11dd5ed48f61"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Constructing a ",
 Cell[BoxData["QuantumCircuitOperator"], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "742fd3f3-9c3c-4a8c-b0a1-20347f216bff"],
 " with ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox["10", "4"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "06df16a9-d8f4-4a7d-9f62-278cdab9df4a"],
 " or more gates carries host-framework overhead; for long streams one should \
hand the gate-spec list to ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"ps", "[", "gates", "]"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "bd304cb9-dad5-4f38-b46c-246ef386f1ff"],
 " directly."
}], "Item",ExpressionUUID->"1b65381b-5a56-4ec0-a998-73189c9939f9"],

Cell["\<\
Reconstructing an exact state vector from a gate-updated tableau, or from a \
gate-built stabilizer frame, is correct up to a single global phase, which is \
never observable; only the relative phase between two separately-built \
objects is gauge-limited.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"51d0e95e-4c6f-4e72-9bd0-feeaabdc6d9b"],

Cell["\<\
The summary is the one a physicist would want: for raw Clifford throughput \
the specialized engines are a few times faster, and if that is the only thing \
one needs, they are the right tool. For stabilizer simulation that has to \
interoperate with the rest of a quantum-mechanics toolkit, carry symbols, \
stay exact, and reach into codes, graph states, magic, and channels, the \
framework buys all of that for a small constant in speed.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"6b60d978-3417-4bab-afd3-03feb31d8f62"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Where this leaves us", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"c6f331ef-4a83-4ea8-b460-247e7ca4b2b3"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "We built the stabilizer formalism from one idea, that a state is named by \
what fixes it, and rode it from a single qubit to a thousand. Along the way \
the concrete tools were: ",
 Cell[BoxData["PauliStabilizer"], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "c95ea44c-3a92-43a7-bac6-b52ef276ea82"],
 " for states, codes, and the tableau; the gate-update methods and the \
circuit-list form ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"ps", "[", "gates", "]"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "fd424721-3354-4501-b7a8-59154f752b1e"],
 " for Clifford evolution; ",
 Cell[BoxData["\"\<M\>\""], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "6c478add-4608-47b5-8d6c-9b822c6ef102"],
 ", ",
 Cell[BoxData["\"\<Expectation\>\""], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "aece865d-85fa-499b-93c4-795c37f41ed7"],
 ", and ",
 Cell[BoxData["\"\<SymbolicMeasure\>\""], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "e42147b0-1d5c-460a-bad0-e86f63386928"],
 " for measurement; ",
 Cell[BoxData["\"\<Entropy\>\""], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "62521000-aa1a-4528-a2f2-fbd1639269d7"],
 " for entanglement; ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"PauliStabilizer", "[", 
   RowBox[{"\"\<Random\>\"", "[", "n", "]"}], "]"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "7c19c4fc-77ea-430d-9d00-3018b57ef7d4"],
 " for sampling; and ",
 Cell[BoxData["GraphState"], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "c00609c0-5eb7-4ea4-b461-a3d338e5e4d2"],
 ", ",
 Cell[BoxData["StabilizerFrame"], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "fa20018a-61e0-479d-92b4-ff13bd9781d4"],
 ", and ",
 Cell[BoxData["CliffordChannel"], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "d89bf618-0053-4717-95c0-c88c2f962272"],
 " for the frontier."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"63c41171-ca52-4af5-97b4-67a38a34c3a2"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The natural next steps are the ones the formalism opens onto: syndrome \
decoding on the codes of the error-correction section, stabilizer-rank \
simulation of magic-rich circuits via the frame, and Clifford-channel models \
of realistic noise. Each is a short extension of the computations in this \
document, and each stays, as long as it can, inside the ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["O", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["(",
    SpanMaxSize->1], 
   SuperscriptBox[
    StyleBox["n", "TI"], "2"], 
   StyleBox[")",
    SpanMaxSize->1]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "5f5ebd4d-e142-4282-b4b1-864dd4f4f4c2"],
 " tableau that makes the whole subject tractable."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"8b33488a-e716-43c3-9ec6-bcdd5ea016c1"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The key references underpinning the implementation are ",
 ButtonBox["Gottesman's stabilizer-codes thesis (1997)",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["https://arxiv.org/abs/quant-ph/9705052"], None}],
 ", ",
 ButtonBox["Aaronson and Gottesman on the tableau and its measurement update \
(2004)",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["https://arxiv.org/abs/quant-ph/0406196"], None}],
 ", ",
 ButtonBox["Fattal and collaborators on stabilizer entanglement entropy \
(2004)",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["https://arxiv.org/abs/quant-ph/0406168"], None}],
 ", ",
 ButtonBox["Anders and Briegel on graph states and local complementation \
(2005)",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["https://arxiv.org/abs/quant-ph/0504117"], None}],
 ", ",
 ButtonBox["Koenig and Smolin on the random-Clifford sampler (2014)",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["https://arxiv.org/abs/1406.2170"], None}],
 ", ",
 ButtonBox["Garcia and Markov on stabilizer frames (2015)",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["https://arxiv.org/abs/1712.03554"], None}],
 ", ",
 ButtonBox["Fang and Ying on symbolic phases (2023)",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["https://arxiv.org/abs/2311.03906"], None}],
 ", and ",
 ButtonBox["Yashin on Clifford channels (2025)",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["https://arxiv.org/abs/2504.14101"], None}],
 "."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"1341a36f-87de-43b9-914e-81f91ff5990d"]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]]
},
